transcript.message: Hi Andy, how are you doing? Would you like to talk about a matter?
I would like to talk about matter please, yes.
Great! I'm here to help you document a matter for your Chambers submission. This should take about 5 minutes. Shall we begin?
Sure, let's do it.
First, is this matter confidential or can it be published?
It's not confidential.
Understood. What is the client's name? If it's confidential, please give me a general description like 'a leading European bank' or 'a major technology company'.
The client is Jean-Louis David
Could you spell that for me, please?
J E A N space L O U I S space D A V I D
Thank you. Can you briefly describe what this matter is about and why it was important?

Yes so they were suffering from significant antisocial behaviour due to the proximity to the KFC and Milano Porto Genova tram stations and I helped them to generate eviction notices for the various different unruly characters.
What specific role did your department play in this matter?

So we researched the various different local bylaws. We included Bobino, who were a close proximity client to ours, and we basically looked at how we could support the client to get the outcomes they needed.
What work did your team complete on this matter in the past 12 months specifically?

So in the last 12 months we undertook the final stages of the eviction notices for the other unruly clients, unruly residents in the area. There was lots of local vandalism and graffiti including lots of lime scooters that were dispersed throughout the city.
Why was this matter particularly important to your client, your firm, or the broader legal market? Was it precedent-setting?

It was precedent setting because it was the first time we'd worked with the Milan local authorities on a high profile eviction case. It also involved several other jurisdictions, including Poland, Portugal, Israel and Botswana.

Let me make sure I've captured this correctly. Your team assisted Jean-Louis David, who was experiencing significant antisocial behavior due to the proximity of KFC and Milano Porto Genova tram stations. In the past 12 months, your team finalized eviction notices for unruly residents, addressing issues like local vandalism, graffiti, and dispersed lime scooters. This matter was precedent-setting as it was the first time your firm worked with Milan local authorities on a high-profile eviction case, and it involved multiple jurisdictions including Poland, Portugal, Israel, and Botswana. Does that sound right?
Correct.
What was the value or deal size of this matter? Please include the currency.
40,000 euros.
So that's forty thousand euros. Was this a cross-border matter involving multiple jurisdictions?
Yes, it was.
Which jurisdictions were involved? I'll list them as you tell me.
I've just told you, you know that.
You're absolutely right, I apologize. You mentioned Poland, Portugal, Israel, and Botswana. Any others?
No
Okay, so that's a cross-border matter involving Poland, Portugal, Israel, Botswana, and Italy. Who was the lead lawyer on this matter?
The lead lawyer was Lee Curtis
Which office are you or they based in?

I'm in... so my name is Andy Batty I am based in Milan Lee Curtis is based in Rome and then there are team members including Andy Turner in Northampton, Simon Martin in Derby, Stuart Pratt in Birmingham.
Thank you, Andy. And which practice group do you or Lee belong to?
I am in the disputes team.
Were there other team members from your firm involved in this matter?
Yes, there were. I've already mentioned them.

Thanks, Andy. Let's confirm the other team members, their offices, and practice groups. You mentioned Andy Turner in Northampton, Simon Martin in Derby, and Stuart Pratt in Birmingham. Could you confirm their practice groups?
Yeah so Simon is within data protection, Stuart is within the intellectual protocol and Andy Turner works within parking regulation and by-laws.
